# Reference accessed: 2026-05-30 via gh api.
#
# irust is the **cross-platform Rust REPL** by sigmaSd
# — interactive evaluator for Rust expressions and
# statements, similar to Python's `python -i` or
# Node.js's `node` REPL.  Pivots from C POSIX getopt
# (R272 blink) into the **REPL tooling cluster**.
# Sister to evcxr (Jupyter Rust kernel REPL), rustyline
# (Rust REPL library), miri (Rust interpreter).
# **MAJOR MILESTONE**: corpus's **first documented
# library-less Rust CLI** — adds the "no library"
# category to the Rust CLI taxonomy (now 4 sub-categories:
# clap derive / clap builder / clap v3 / **hand-rolled**).
#
# Critical extraction note: irust uses **hand-rolled
# Rust CLI parsing** with NO library at all — corpus's
# **first documented library-less Rust CLI** at args.rs
# lines 16-37.  The entire parser is:
# ```
#   pub fn parse_args(args: &[String]) -> ParsedArgs {
#       let mut parsed = ParsedArgs::default();
#       for arg in args {
#           match arg.as_str() {
#               "-h" | "--help" => parsed.show_help = true,
#               "-v" | "--version" => parsed.show_version = true,
#               "--reset-config" => parsed.reset_config = true,
#               "--default-config" => parsed.default_config = true,
#               "--bare-repl" => parsed.bare_repl = true,
#               _ => { /* heuristic positional */ }
#           }
#       }
#       parsed
#   }
# ```
# Documents the **hand-rolled CLI pattern in Rust** —
# distinct from R272 blink's C getopt (which uses the
# stdlib library) and distinct from every other Rust
# CLI in the corpus (which use clap derive / builder /
# v3).  Extends the Rust CLI sub-taxonomy to FOUR
# categories: (a) clap derive (R247-R262, R268), (b)
# clap builder (R259 hyperfine), (c) clap v3 (R261
# replibyte), (d) **hand-rolled** (R273 irust).
# Documents the **lib-vs-no-lib trade-off**: writing
# your own parser is more code but zero dependencies
# (great for small REPLs / simple tools); using clap
# brings auto-help, validation, ValueEnum, subcommand
# routing, but adds ~100ms to compile time and several
# transitive dependencies.  irust's parser is 38 lines
# total — feasible without a library because the CLI
# surface is tiny (5 flags + 1 positional).
#
# Critical extraction note: irust uses **`|` pattern
# guards** in match arms at args.rs:21-25 — `"-h" |
# "--help" => parsed.show_help = true` is one arm with
# 2 patterns; Rust's `|` in a `match` pattern means
# "match if any of these patterns".  Documents the
# **Rust match-`|`-pattern for flag-alias handling** —
# the simplest way to declare short/long flag
# equivalence without a library.  Distinct from R263
# lazygit's flaggy `String(&var, "h", "help", ...)`
# (which separates short and long params).
#
# Critical extraction note: irust uses **HEURISTIC
# POSITIONAL** at args.rs:27-32 — when an arg doesn't
# match any flag, irust checks if it ENDS WITH `.rs`
# (Rust source extension).  If yes, it's treated as a
# script_path; if no, it's added to `unknown_args` Vec
# for diagnostic reporting.  Documents the **extension-
# based positional disambiguation** pattern — useful
# when CLIs accept files of a specific type without
# requiring a flag prefix.  Distinct from clap derive's
# explicit `#[arg]` positional declarations.  Plus the
# code at main.rs:96-98 logs unknown_args to stderr
# WITHOUT exiting (warning, not error) — irust is
# tolerant of unknown args.  Corpus's first documented
# extension-based positional disambiguation.
#
# Critical extraction note: irust uses **stdin-as-input
# detection** at main.rs:54-93 — `if args.is_empty()`
# AND `!stdin.is_tty()`, irust reads stdin to EOF and
# evaluates the content as a one-shot Rust expression.
# This makes irust usable as a Unix filter:
# `echo "1 + 1" | irust` outputs `2`.  Documents the
# **pipe-mode auto-detection pattern** — distinct from
# R248 cairo-coverage's explicit file positional and
# from R265 moq's positional-args-required.  irust
# AUTO-DETECTS the mode based on whether stdin is a
# terminal.  Corpus's **first documented `stdin.is_tty
# ()` mode-switching** pattern.  Used by many Unix
# tools (e.g. `cat -` reads stdin, `grep pattern`
# defaults to stdin when no file arg).
#
# Critical extraction note: irust uses **manual help-
# text string** at main.rs:19-46 — since there's no
# library to auto-generate `--help`, the developer
# writes the help text as a multi-line `println!`
# format string with embedded `{}` placeholders for
# VERSION and config_path.  Documents the **manual
# help-text pattern** — costs ~30 lines of code but
# offers full control over formatting.  Distinct from
# clap derive's `#[command(about = "...")]` auto-help.

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line

# 5 flags + 1 heuristic positional (`.rs` file).
# Decoded source-direct from parse_args at args.rs:20-25.
_arguments -s \
  '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[show help and exit (manual help-text string)]' \
  '(-v --version)'{-v,--version}'[show IRust version and exit]' \
  '--reset-config[reset IRust configuration to defaults]' \
  '--default-config[use default configuration for this run (not saved)]' \
  '--bare-repl[start IRust in bare REPL mode]' \
  '1::Rust source file to load (heuristic: .rs extension):_files -g "*.rs"'
